> From my (superficial) understanding of how TF gets data to TB, it is (eventually) by crafting protobuf instances and serializing them to the tfevents files on disk which then get handled/processed by the event accumulator code.

Correct.

> What if I just designed my own .proto for the "high" level data I'd like to send e.g. consisting of its own fields like image tensors, labels, etc? 

I see what you're asking. The problem is—how do we implement that? As you mentioned, we need to get data out of the graph, and the way that we do that is with an op that takes in the relevant tensor data and serializes it to a protobuf. So far, so good; this is compatible with your vision. Now, currently (moving forward) we use the `TensorSummary` op for everything, and this op accepts a single tensor and stores it into the `tensor` field of the protobuf. But if you want to do something else, which is your whole goal, then the op itself needs to know about your protobuf. You'd have to write a C++ "kernel" for the op that wired up the data to your protobuf.

For instance, [here's the kernel for the `TensorSummary` op.](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/863d7e7f0202cf5b513f2e3e691e7686562c8d74/tensorflow/core/kernels/summary_tensor_op.cc#L38) If you wanted your `WidgetPlugin` to write a protobuf like
```proto
message WidgetSummaryData {
  string tag = 0;
  int32 widget_count = 1;
  bytes widget_factory_name = 2;
  repeated float production_status = 3;
}
```
then you would want a kernel to do something like this:
```cpp
void Compute(OpKernelContext* c) override {
  const Tensor& tag = c->input(0);
  const Tensor& widget_count = c->input(1);
  const Tensor& widget_factory_name = c->input(2);
  const Tensor& production_status = c->input(2);
  OP_REQUIRES(c, TensorShapeUtils::IsScalar(tag.shape()),
              errors::InvalidArgument("tag must be scalar"));
  OP_REQUIRES(c, TensorShapeUtils::IsScalar(widget_count.shape()),
              errors::InvalidArgument("widget_count must be scalar"));
  OP_REQUIRES(c, TensorShapeUtils::IsScalar(widget_factory_name.shape()),
              errors::InvalidArgument("widget_factory_name must be scalar"));
  OP_REQUIRES(c, TensorShapeUtils::IsVector(production_status.shape()),
              errors::InvalidArgument("production_status must be vector"));


  WidgetSummary s;
  s->set_tag(tag.scalar<string>()());
  s->set_widget_count(tag.widget_count<int32>()());
  s->set_widget_factory_name(tag.widget_count<string>()());
  for (int32 i = 0; i < production_status->NumElements(); i++) {
    s->add_production_status(production_status.flat<float>()(i));
  }

  Tensor* output = nullptr;
  OP_REQUIRES_OK(c, c->allocate_output(0, TensorShape({}), &output));
  CHECK(s.SerializeToString(&output->scalar<string>()()));
}
```
So now you have a C++ dependency in your project, which probably isn't what you want.

Furthermore, once you get that protobuf out of your op, you'd have a `WidgetSummary` protobuf and not a standard `Summary` protobuf. The file writer needs a `Summary` protobuf, because it writes [`Event`s](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/863d7e7f0202cf5b513f2e3e691e7686562c8d74/tensorflow/core/util/event.proto), and [`Event`s contain `Summary`s](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/863d7e7f0202cf5b513f2e3e691e7686562c8d74/tensorflow/core/util/event.proto#L29), not arbitrary protos.

So you'd have to change the core `Event` proto so that it can also contain something like a `bytes arbitrary_proto` content…but now you don't know how to decode it in TensorBoard (there are `WidgetSummary`s and `MacGuffinSummary`s; how do you tell them apart?)…so maybe you add some more metadata to the `Event` proto…

Do you see why this is kind of a hard problem? It's not that it's a _bad_ design, but it's pretty fundamentally different from what the rest of TensorBoard uses, and so it would be very tricky to integrate.

